{"title_page": "Barron Hilton", "text_new": "{{short description|American hotelier}}\n{{for|the peerage title|Baron Hylton}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| birth_name         = William Barron Hilton\n| name               = Barron Hilton\n| image              = Barron Hilton.JPEG\n| caption            = Barron Hilton in 2007\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|mf=yes|1927|10|23}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dallas, Texas]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2019|9|19|1927|10|23}}\n| death_place        = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| father             = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Southern California]] Aeronautical School\n| occupation         = [[Business]] [[magnate]], [[philanthropist]] and sportsman\n| net_worth          = US$3.4&nbsp;billion<ref name=\"McNulty 2019\">{{cite web | last=McNulty | first=Matthew | title=Barron Hilton leaves 97% of massive fortune to this foundation | website=Fox Business | date=September 22, 2019 | url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/business-leaders/barron-hilton-fortune-estate-foundation | access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n| spouse             = Marilyn June Hawley (1947\u20132004)\n| children           = 8\n| parents            = {{plain list|\n* [[Conrad Nicholson Hilton]]\n* Mary Adelaide Hilton\n}}\n| relatives          = {{plain list|\n* [[Conrad Nicholson Hilton, Jr.]]  {{small|(brother)}}\n* [[Eric Hilton|Eric Michael Hilton]] {{small|(brother)}}\n* [[Francesca Hilton]] {{small|(half-sister)}}\n* [[Paris Hilton]] {{small|(granddaughter)}}\n* [[Nicky Hilton Rothschild]] {{small|(granddaughter)}}\n}}\n| signature          = Barron_Hilton_Signature.png\n}}\n'''William Barron Hilton''' (October 23, 1927 \u2013 September 19, 2019) was an American [[business magnate]], philanthropist and sportsman. The second son and successor of hotelier [[Conrad Hilton]], he was the chairman, president and chief executive officer of [[Hilton Hotels Corporation]] and chairman emeritus of the [[Conrad N. Hilton Foundation]]. Hilton, a notable pilot and outdoorsman, was also a founder of the [[American Football League]] as the original owner of the [[Los Angeles Chargers]], and helped forge the merger with the [[National Football League]] that created the [[Super Bowl]]. Like his father before him, he pledged 97 percent of his wealth to the humanitarian work of the [[Conrad N. Hilton Foundation]].<ref>\"Barron Hilton to Donate 97% of Estate to Hilton Foundation\". Planned Giving Design Center, LLC. December 26, 2007. Retrieved April 2, 2011.</ref> At the time, the gift was projected to increase the foundation's endowment from $2.9&nbsp;billion to $6.3&nbsp;billion,<ref>Haggerty, James R., \"Hilton Founder's Son Sought His Own Path,\" ''Wall Street Journal'', 2019-9-21, p. A6</ref> and will make his estate the organization's most significant donor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hiltonfoundation.org/news/453-conrad-n-hilton-foundation-announces-the-death-of-barron-hilton|title=Conrad N. Hilton Foundation Announces the Death of Barron Hilton|first=Conrad N. Hilton|last=Foundation 818.851.3700|website=Conrad N. Hilton Foundation|accessdate=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nHilton was born in [[Dallas]], [[Texas]], to Mary Adelaide (n\u00e9e Barron) and [[Conrad Hilton|Conrad Nicholson Hilton]], founder of [[Hilton Hotels]]. Hilton grew up with three siblings, [[Conrad Hilton, Jr.|Conrad Nicholson Hilton, Jr.]], Eric Michael Hilton, and Constance Francesca Hilton. His father was of Norwegian and German descent, and his mother was from Kentucky.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wargs.com/other/hilton.html |title=Ancestry of Paris Hilton |publisher=Wargs.com (blog) |date=<!--undated--> |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605185352/http://www.wargs.com/other/hilton.html |archive-date=June 5, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHe served in the [[United States Navy|Navy]] during [[World War II]] as a photographer. As a child, Hilton was fascinated by aviation, and learned to fly when he was 17. After his wartime discharge, he attended the [[University of Southern California]] Aeronautical School, where he earned his [[twin-engine]] rating at age 19.<ref>{{cite web |last=Robertson |first=Cliff |title=Smashing Stereotypes |publisher=Airport Journals |date=June 2006 |url=http://www.airportjournals.com/Display.cfm?varID=0606003 |accessdate=April 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717065651/http://www.airportjournals.com/Display.cfm?varID=0606003 |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Early career, Los Angeles Chargers ==\nBefore joining his father in the hotel industry, Barron Hilton honed his business skills in a variety of entrepreneurial ventures. He acquired the Los Angeles-area distributorship of Vita-Pakt Citrus Products, co-founded MacDonald Oil Company, and founded Air Finance Corporation, one of the nation's first aircraft leasing businesses. In 1954, Barron was elected vice president of Hilton Hotels, running the company's franchise operations and creating the [[Carte Blanche (credit card)|Carte Blanche]] credit card as a service to the company's customers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hrm.uh.edu/inductee/inductee.asp?InducteeId=52&id= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326065330/http://www.hrm.uh.edu/inductee/inductee.asp?InducteeId=52&id= |title=Hospitality Hall of Honor \u2013 Inductees \u2013 Barron Hilton |website=[[University of Houston]] |date=<!--undated--> |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |archive-date=March 26, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1959, [[Lamar Hunt]] offered Hilton the Los Angeles franchise in the new [[American Football League]] (AFL). Hilton named his team the [[Chargers]], but denied that he did it to create synergy with his new credit card business. A fan had nominated the name in a contest, and Hilton selected it because of the bugle call and \"Charge!\" cheer that was often sounded during [[USC Trojans football|USC football]] games at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]]. The Chargers began playing at the Coliseum in 1960, but in spite of winning the [[Western Division (NFL)|Western Division]], the club found it difficult to compete for fans with the [[Los Angeles Rams|Rams]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL) in their own stadium. Hilton moved the team to San Diego in time for the [[1961 NFL season|1961 season]] and played in tiny [[Balboa Stadium]], which the city had expanded to 30,000 seats.<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/nov/30/sports/la-sp-dwyre30-2009nov30 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Bill |last=Dwyre |title=Barron Hilton's Chargers turned short stay into long-term success |date=November 30, 2009 |access-date=December 13, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107195724/http://articles.latimes.com/2009/nov/30/sports/la-sp-dwyre30-2009nov30 |archive-date=January 7, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHilton began working with the local newspapers to engender support for construction of a state-of-the-art stadium. Encouraged by [[San Diego Union]] sports editor [[Jack Murphy (sportswriter)|Jack Murphy]], among others, a referendum was passed in 1965, and the Chargers began play in the new San Diego Stadium in 1967. With the availability of a new stadium, the city received a baseball expansion franchise from the National League, and the [[San Diego Padres]] began play in 1969. It was named Jack Murphy Stadium after Murphy's death in 1980, and is now known as [[SDCCU Stadium]].<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\" />\n\nHilton also served as AFL president in 1965, and helped forge the merger between the AFL and the NFL, announced in 1966, which created the Super Bowl. In all, the Chargers won five divisional titles, and one [[AFL Championship]], during Hilton's six years at the helm of the club. In 1966, directors of Hilton Hotels Corporation asked Hilton to succeed his father as president and chief executive officer of the company, provided that he drop his football responsibilities. He sold his majority interest in the team for $10&nbsp;million\u2014a record for any professional sports franchise at the time\u2014after an initial investment in a franchise fee of just $25,000.<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\" />\n\nWith the death of the Bills' [[Ralph Wilson]] in 2014, Hilton became the last surviving member of the [[Foolish Club]]\u2014the nickname the original AFL owners gave each other, as they absorbed the start-up expenses and player salaries necessary to compete with the established NFL.<ref name = NYTObit/>\n\n==Hilton Hotels==\nOnce charged with the responsibility for Hilton Hotels Corporation, Barron Hilton soon showed his father's genius for cost controls and real estate deals. In 1970, he convinced the board to expand into [[Las Vegas]] by purchasing the International and the Flamingo from financier [[Kirk Kerkorian]]. Hilton Hotels thus became the first company listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] to venture into the gaming market. Renamed the [[Las Vegas Hilton]] and the [[Flamingo Hilton]], the two resorts tapped a new source of income from gambling in a state where it had been legal since 1931. Barron could also see that Las Vegas would become a leading convention destination, capitalizing on the company's strength in that important market segment.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1970 Annual Report, pp. 12\u201316</ref>\n\nHilton personally introduced two innovations that have become standard features of casinos everywhere. Calling on his background in photography, he installed video cameras throughout the casinos to replace the \"eye in the sky\" system of observers peering through two-way mirrors in the ceiling.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pregame.com/sample_weblogs/b/bob-majors/archive/2008/09/07/old-school-las-vegas-then-las-vegas-now-as-perceived-by-bob-majors.aspx |title=Old School \u2013 Las Vegas Then/Las Vegas Now as perceived by Bob Majors \u2013 Bob Majors \u2013 Sample Weblogs |publisher=Pregame.com |date=September 7, 2008 |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |first=Bob |last=Majors |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528200436/http://pregame.com/sample_weblogs/b/bob-majors/archive/2008/09/07/old-school-las-vegas-then-las-vegas-now-as-perceived-by-bob-majors.aspx |archivedate=May 28, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nLas Vegas would also become the self-proclaimed \"Entertainment Capital of the World\". Of all the headliners to perform at the Hilton or the Flamingo, the most successful and spectacular was [[Elvis Presley]]. After a decade in the movies, he began performing in front of live audiences again in 1969 at the opening of the International (a few years later renamed the Las Vegas Hilton). He went on to star at the Las Vegas Hilton two months a year\u2014performing two shows a night, seven nights a week\u2014until shortly before his death in 1977. Presley set a world entertainment record at the Las Vegas Hilton for selling out 837 consecutive concerts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/news/2012/dec/13/25-greatest-headliners-las-vegas-history/ |title=The 25 greatest headliners in Las Vegas history |publisher=Las Vegas Weekly |date=December 13, 2012 |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607190605/http://lasvegasweekly.com/news/2012/dec/13/25-greatest-headliners-las-vegas-history/ |archive-date=June 7, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe company's expansion into Nevada had an immediate impact on its net income. By 1972, the two resorts contributed 45 percent of the company's income (before interest income, interest expense, write down of investments and sales of properties), nearly matching the income from the other 160 Hilton hotels in the United States.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1973 Annual Report, p. 2</ref>\n\nOn the hotel front, in 1975, Hilton sold a 50 percent interest in six of the company's largest hotels to [[Prudential Insurance Company]] for $83&nbsp;million. He took a [[leaseback]] to manage the properties, collecting lucrative management fees and a percentage of their gross profits. Perhaps more importantly, the sale proved that these hotels were worth double their book value, demonstrating the underlying value of the company's real estate holdings.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1976 Annual Report, p. 5</ref> The transaction also enhanced the value of the stock held by every HHC shareholder. Hilton used the proceeds to pay down high interest debt, and repurchase 20 percent of the company's stock\u2014all at [[market rate]]\u2014which was still trading well below the company's book value.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1975 Annual Report, p. 4</ref>\n\nHilton continued to expand the domestic hotel chain through franchising and the selective acquisition of management contracts and hotels in emerging markets. In 1977, he completed a hotel purchase that his father had initiated 28 years earlier. When Conrad Hilton bought the [[Waldorf-Astoria]] in 1949, he actually bought the hotel's operating company and its 30-year lease to run the hotel. The building, and the land under it, were still owned by the realty arm of the [[Penn Central Railroad]]. Knowing that the lease would expire in 1979, Hilton deftly negotiated to buy the hotel and real estate from the railroad. The landmark property, whose current value is estimated around $1&nbsp;billion, was purchased by Hilton for just $35&nbsp;million.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1976 Annual Report, p. 3</ref> \n\t\nAs competitors aggressively spread across the U.S. in the '80s, Barron held his own by rehabbing his own hotels and increasing revenues in Las Vegas. Through a series of massive additions to the Flamingo Hilton and the Las Vegas Hilton, the company nearly tripled its rooms in Las Vegas by 1990, from 2,277 to 6,703. He also launched Conrad International in the '80s,<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1990 Annual Report, p. 7</ref> and [[Hilton Garden Inn]] in the '90s.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1996 Annual Report, p. 5</ref>\n\nIn contrast to his gamble on gaming, Hilton earned a well-deserved reputation as a financial conservative. After seeing his father struggle to overcome the effects of the [[American Great Depression]] and [[World War II]], he maintained the strongest [[balance sheet]] in the industry. Throughout his 30 years as CEO, he carried a low [[debt-to-capital ratio]] and a high [[credit rating]], enabling him to gobble up such properties as [[Bally's Reno]] (formerly the MGM Grand Hotel and Casino-Reno). The 2,000-room resort was opened in 1978 for $230&nbsp;million, and purchased by Hilton in 1992 for $88&nbsp;million. With strong [[cash flow]] and plenty of liquid investments on hand, he was able to weather the inevitable recessions and business interruptions that struck the industry from the mid-'60s to the mid-'90s.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation 1992 Annual Report, pp. 3\u20134</ref>\n \nHilton continued as chairman of the board through the next decade as his hand-picked successor, [[Steve Bollenbach]], dramatically expanded the company through a series of mergers and acquisitions. The advent of friendly capital markets in the late '90s enabled him to acquire such popular brands as [[Embassy Suites]], [[Doubletree]], [[Hampton Inn]], [[Homewood Suites]], Bally's and Caesars.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1999 Annual Report, p. 2</ref> Then, in 2005, he reacquired Hilton International, 38 years after it had been sold to TWA. With the company now strategically complete, Bollenbach spun off the gaming business, which merged with Harrah's in 2005 and was renamed [[Caesars Entertainment Corporation|Caesars Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.webpronews.com/caesars-and-harrahs-to-merge-2005-03 |title=Caesars and Harrah's To Merge |publisher=WebProNews.com |date=March 11, 2005 |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217224227/http://www.webpronews.com/caesars-and-harrahs-to-merge-2005-03 |archive-date=December 17, 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the meantime, the hotel business continued to soar. With the best known and most respected name in the industry\u2014and popular domestic brands ripe for expansion overseas\u2014Hilton Hotels Corporation proved to be irresistible to [[The Blackstone Group]]. In 2007, the private equity firm purchased Hilton Hotels Corporation, consisting of 2,800 hotels with 480,000 rooms in 76 countries and territories. Blackstone paid $47.50 per share, a 32 percent premium over the July 2 closing price. The $26&nbsp;billion, all-cash transaction included $7.5&nbsp;billion of debt.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blackstone.com/news-views/press-releases/hilton-hotels-corporation-to-be-acquired-by-blackstone-investments-funds |title=Hilton Hotels Corporation to be Acquired by Blackstone Investments Funds |publisher=Blackstone.com |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528221158/http://www.blackstone.com/news-views/press-releases/hilton-hotels-corporation-to-be-acquired-by-blackstone-investments-funds |archive-date=May 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Host Hotels & Resorts]] veteran Chris Nassetta was hired to manage the company, which was renamed [[Hilton Worldwide]], Inc. and is now known as Hilton, Inc. Now celebrating the 100th year since Conrad Hilton purchased his first hotel, the company has expanded to include 17 brands, 5,800 hotels, and 939,000 rooms in 114 countries of the world.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hilton.com/en/corporate/ |title=Hilton Brands &#124; Global Hospitality Company |access-date=September 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903041043/https://www.hilton.com/en/corporate/ |archive-date=September 3, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> With another 373,000 rooms in the development pipeline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsroom.hilton.com/corporate/news/hilton-reports-second-quarter-results-exceeds-net-income-and-adjusted-ebitda-expectations|title=Hilton Reports Second Quarter Results; Exceeds Net Income and Adjusted EBITDA Expectations|website=Hilton Press Center|accessdate=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Hilton family fortune ==\nIn 1979, Barron Hilton's father, [[Conrad Hilton]], died at age 91. He left 13.5&nbsp;million shares of Hilton Hotels Corporation stock\u201497 percent of his estate\u2014to the [[Conrad N. Hilton Foundation]], a humanitarian charity which he had established in 1944.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia: Barron Hilton\">{{cite encyclopedia |title=Hilton, William \u2013 Overview, Personal Life, Career Details, Social and Economic Impact, Chronology: Hilton, William |publisher=Net Industries |url=http://encyclopedia.jrank.org/articles/pages/6273/Hilton-William.html |format=Encyclopedia |accessdate=April 2, 2011 |date=<!--undated--> |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215163811/http://encyclopedia.jrank.org/articles/pages/6273/Hilton-William.html |archivedate=February 15, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn his will, Conrad also gave Barron the right to purchase those shares in order to maintain family control of the company, but the foundation challenged the option in [[probate court]]. It took an entire decade to resolve the issue. Hilton's right to exercise his option was upheld in an appeals court ruling in March 1988, giving him [[Voting interest|voting power]] over roughly 34 percent of the company's [[outstanding shares]]. Conrad's bequest of stock was worth $160&nbsp;million when he died in 1979. Thanks to his son's successful management of the Hilton Hotels Corporation, those shares were worth $654&nbsp;million when the settlement was reached late in 1988. In a press statement issued after the favorable ruling, Hilton said it gave him \"the opportunity to structure an arrangement whereby my father's two objectives, retaining control of the stock in family hands, and benefiting charity through the Conrad N. Hilton Foundation, can both be achieved. I am confident that my father would be pleased with this accord.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-11-26/business/fi-240_1_barron-hilton |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |first=Al |last=Delugach |title=Barron Hilton Wins Battle for Chain : Settlement of Lengthy Dispute Gives Hotelier Effective Control |date=November 26, 1988 |access-date=December 13, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218125601/http://articles.latimes.com/1988-11-26/business/fi-240_1_barron-hilton |archive-date=December 18, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe settlement was finalized in 1989. Neither Hilton, nor the foundation, had to actually pay for the shares; they split them instead. Hilton received 4 million shares, the Conrad N. Hilton Foundation received 3.5&nbsp;million shares, and the remaining 6&nbsp;million shares were placed in the W. Barron Hilton [[Charitable remainder unitrust]], of which Barron was the executor. He received 60 percent of the unitrust income, and the foundation 40 percent, during his lifetime, then the fund would transfer to the foundation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-05-12/business/fi-2998_1_barron-hilton-founder-s-estate-conrad-n-hilton-foundation |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Al |last=Delugach |title=Hilton Open to Offers but No Deal Pending, CEO Says |date=May 12, 1989 |access-date=December 13, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218125604/http://articles.latimes.com/1989-05-12/business/fi-2998_1_barron-hilton-founder-s-estate-conrad-n-hilton-foundation |archive-date=December 18, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn December 25, 2007, Hilton announced that he would follow in his father's footsteps by leaving about 97 percent of his estate, estimated at that time to be $2.3&nbsp;billion, to the [[Conrad N. Hilton Foundation]].<ref name=\"PGDC\">{{cite web |title=Barron Hilton to Donate 97% of Estate to Hilton Foundation |date=December 26, 2007 |publisher=Planned Giving Design Center, LLC |url=http://www.pgdc.com/pgdc/news-story/2007/12/27/barron-hilton-donate-97-estate-hilton-foundation |accessdate=April 2, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319015235/http://www.pgdc.com/pgdc/news-story/2007/12/27/barron-hilton-donate-97-estate-hilton-foundation |archive-date=March 19, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7161358.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |title=Hilton fortune to go to charity |date=December 27, 2007 |accessdate=April 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206182754/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7161358.stm |archive-date=December 6, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> Included was an immediate pledge of $1.2&nbsp;billion, the proceeds of the sale of Hilton Hotels Corporation and Harrah's Entertainment Inc., which was placed in a [[charitable remainder unitrust]] that would be transferred to the foundation upon Hilton's death at whatever value the trust was worth at that time.<ref name=\"PGDC\"/><ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-12-26-hilton-donate_N.htm |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |title=Hilton to donate bulk of fortune to foundation |date=December 27, 2007 |accessdate=April 2, 2011 |first=Roger |last=Yu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530163049/http://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-12-26-hilton-donate_N.htm |archive-date=May 30, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The remainder of the funds that constitute Hilton's pledge of 97 percent of his estate will come from his personal assets, which were estimated at $1.1&nbsp;billion at the time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/30/business/30suits.html|title=A Hilton in the News (and It's Not Paris)|last=Olson|first=Elizabeth|date=December 30, 2007|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 2, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402143623/https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/30/business/30suits.html|archive-date=April 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Conrad N. Hilton Foundation==\nThroughout his career, Conrad Hilton supported a variety of causes, particularly those involving the nuns that had helped educate him in his native [[New Mexico]]. He established the [[Conrad N. Hilton Foundation]] in 1944, and made a total of $7.6&nbsp;million of gifts before his death.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hiltonfoundation.org/about/history |title=History |website=Hiltonfoundation.org |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107195726/https://www.hiltonfoundation.org/about/history |archive-date=January 7, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn his last will and testament, Conrad left general guidance for the use of his endowment. He wrote: \"There is a natural law, a Divine law, that obliges you and me to relieve the suffering, the distressed and the destitute. Charity is a supreme virtue, and the great channel through which the mercy of God is passed on to mankind. It is the virtue that unites men and inspires their noblest efforts. 'Love one another, for that is the whole law;' so our fellow men deserve to be loved and encouraged\u2014never abandoned to wander alone in poverty and darkness. The practice of charity will bind us\u2014will bind all men in one great brotherhood. As the funds you will expend have come from many places in the world, so let there be no territorial, religious, or color restrictions on your benefactions, but beware of organized, professional charities with high-salaried executives and a heavy ratio of expense. Be ever watchful for the opportunity to shelter little children with the umbrella of your charity; be generous to their schools, their hospitals and their places of worship. For, as they must bear the burdens of our mistakes, so are they in their innocence the repositories of our hopes for the upward progress of humanity. Give aid to their protectors and defenders, the Sisters, who devote their love and life's work for the good of mankind, for they appeal especially to me as being deserving of help from the Foundation.\"<ref>[http://hiltonfoundation.org/last-will ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527043302/http://hiltonfoundation.org/last-will |date=May 27, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Aviation career==\nHilton was born the year [[Charles Lindbergh]] flew the [[Spirit of St. Louis]] across the Atlantic. When he was 7 or 8 years old, he would ride his bike to [[Dallas Love Field|Love Field]] in [[Dallas]] to watch the exotic planes of the day take off and land. He promised himself that he would one day learn to fly. He took private flying lessons at a field on the north shore of Oahu during his time in the Navy, and got his pilot's license at age 17.<ref name=\"airportjournals.com\">[http://www.airportjournals.com/Display.cfm?varID=0307003 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120627093532/http://www.airportjournals.com/Display.cfm?varID=0307003 |date=June 27, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his single-engine and multi-engine ratings, Hilton eventually earned glider, lighter than air (balloons) and helicopter ratings as well. He maintained a small fleet of aircraft at his [[Flying-M Ranch|Flying M Ranch]] east of the sierras in northern Nevada that includes sailplanes, tow planes, aerobatic aircraft, hot air balloons and classic, restored biplanes.<ref name=\"airportjournals.com\"/> He flew them all until he retired from the cockpit in 2012 at age 84.<ref>{{cite book |last=Freeze |first=Di |title=In the Cockpit with Barron Hilton |year=2013 |page=xv |isbn=978-0985810368}}</ref>\n\nIn the '90s, he boldly backed the first attempts to capture one of the last great milestones in aviation\u2014flying non-stop around the world in a balloon\u2014with the Earthwinds Hilton and Global Hilton campaigns. While falling short of the ultimate goal, Hilton is credited with inspiring the efforts of those who achieved the feat. [[Bertrand Piccard]] and [[Brian Jones]] were the first to make a trans-global flight in 1999; [[Steve Fossett]] became the first to complete the flight solo in 2002.<ref name=\"airportjournals.com\"/>\n\nFrom 1980 to 2009, he also hosted the [[Barron Hilton Cup]], a unique, worldwide glider competition. Pilots who flew the longest triangular flights during each two-year period in six regions of the world earned participation in a weeklong soaring camp at his Flying M Ranch. Co-founder [[Helmut Reichmann]], Germany's three-time world soaring champion, devised a handicap system that enabled pilots flying older gliders to compete with elite pilots in high-performance aircraft of the latest design. Once at the Flying M, they flew recreationally alongside world champions and celebrities invited to attend by Hilton. Beginning in 1996 with its predecessors, the European Aeronautic Defence and Space Co., [[EADS]], had served as a partner in the event.<ref name=\"airportjournals.com\"/>\n\nOver the years, a number of notable pilots regularly joined Hilton for weekends at the Flying M. They include entertainers [[John Denver]] and [[Cliff Robertson]]; astronauts [[Neil Armstrong]], [[Gene Cernan]], [[Bill Anders]], and [[Ulf Merbold]]; and test pilots and record-holders Johnny Myers, [[Clay Lacy]], Bruno Gantenbrink, [[Bob Hoover]], [[Carroll Shelby]], Sully Sullenberger, and air, sea and land adventurer, [[Steve Fossett]].<ref name=\"airportjournals.com\"/>\n\nOn Labor Day, 2007, Fossett took off from the Flying M Ranch and never returned, perishing in a crash in the Sierras. In spite of an intensive search, the wreckage wasn't discovered until the following spring. The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause(s) of this accident to be \"the pilot's inadvertent encounter with downdrafts that exceeded the climb capability of the airplane. Contributing to the accident were the downdrafts, high density altitude, and mountainous terrain.\"  Examination of the airframe and engine revealed no evidence of any malfunctions or failures that would have prevented normal operation.<ref>[http://www.ntsb.gov/aviationquery/brief.aspx?ev_id=20081007X17184&key=1 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203023400/http://www.ntsb.gov/aviationquery/brief.aspx?ev_id=20081007X17184&key=1 |date=December 3, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Smithsonian National Air & Space Museum]] honored Hilton in 2010 by christening the Barron Hilton Pioneers of Flight Gallery. The redesigned exhibit recognizes aviators like Lindbergh, [[Amelia Earhart]] and the [[Tuskeegee Airmen]]. The gallery includes an early childhood education component funded by the Hilton Foundation to help youngsters catch the same enthusiasm for aviation that he discovered as a child when Lindbergh and Earhart were making headlines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsdesk.si.edu/releases/barron-hilton-pioneers-flight-gallery-opens-nov-19 |title=\"Barron Hilton Pioneers of Flight Gallery\" Opens Nov. 19 &#124; Newsdesk |publisher=Newsdesk.si.edu |date=November 16, 2010 |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528201234/http://newsdesk.si.edu/releases/barron-hilton-pioneers-flight-gallery-opens-nov-19 |archive-date=May 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Barron was inducted into the [[International Air & Space Hall of Fame]] at the [[San Diego Air & Space Museum]].<ref>Sprekelmeyer, Linda, editor. ''These We Honor: The International Aerospace Hall of Fame''. Donning Co. Publishers, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1-57864-397-4}}.</ref>\n\nFor his lifelong support of aviation, Hilton received the prestigious [[FAI Gold Air Medal]] from the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration A\u00e9ronautique Internationale]] in 2009, the same award bestowed upon some of his closest friends and personal heroes, like Yeager, Armstrong, Cernan, Jones, Fossett, and Lindbergh himself.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fai.org/awards/fai-general-awards |title=General Awards |publisher=Fai.org |date=July 5, 2011 |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420212845/http://www.fai.org/awards/fai-general-awards |archivedate=April 20, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Hilton was also inducted into the International Air & Space Hall of Fame in San Diego, and was hailed as the \"patron saint of sport aviation.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sandiegoairandspace.org/press/release.php?id=60 |title=San Diego Air & Space Museum \u2013 Balboa Park, San Diego |publisher=Sandiegoairandspace.org |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528200331/http://www.sandiegoairandspace.org/press/release.php?id=60 |archive-date=May 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1947, Barron Hilton married Marilyn June Hawley; they remained married until she died in 2004. They had eight children: William Barron Hilton, Jr.; Hawley Anne Hilton; [[Steven M. Hilton|Stephen Michael Hilton]]; David Alan Hilton; Sharon Constance Hilton; [[Richard Hilton|Richard Howard Hilton]]; Daniel Kevin Hilton; and Ronald Jeffrey Hilton; William Barron Hilton, Jr. was born in 1948 and Ronald Jeffrey Hilton was born in 1963. Barron Hilton had 15 grandchildren, including Richard Hilton's daughters [[Paris Hilton]] and [[Nicky Hilton Rothschild]], and four great-grandchildren. \n\nHis primary residence in [[Holmby Hills, Los Angeles|Holmby Hills]] was the [[Jay Paley House]], originally designed in the 1930s for Jay Paley<ref>{{Citation | title = Jay Paley Residence | work = Paul Revere Williams Project Gallery | year = 2010 | url = http://www.paulrwilliamsproject.org/gallery/1930s-houses/ | access-date = March 3, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100503160046/http://www.paulrwilliamsproject.org/gallery/1930s-houses | archive-date = May 3, 2010 | url-status = live }}</ref> by architect [[Paul Williams (architect)|Paul Williams]]. It was used as the 'Colby mansion' in exterior scenes for ''[[The Colbys]]'' television series. He also maintained a permanent suite in New York's Waldorf, and a 475,000-acre ranch called ''Flying M'' stretching across Nevada & California state lines. The ranch included an airport and a two-hole putting green.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lester |first=Peter |date=28 Sep 1981 |title=When This Hotel Barron Says He's Staying at the Hilton, That Means He'll Be at Home |url=https://people.com/archive/when-this-hotel-barron-says-hes-staying-at-the-hilton-that-means-hell-be-at-home-vol-16-no-13/ |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |access-date=8 Apr 2020}}</ref>\n\nHilton died of natural causes at his home in Los Angeles on September 19, 2019.<ref name = NYTObit>{{cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/business/barron-hilton-dead.html|title = Barron Hilton, Hotel Magnate and Founding A.F.L. Owner, Dies at 91|last = Goldstein|first = Richard|date = September 20, 2019|accessdate = September 22, 2019|work = [[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Karimi 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/21/entertainment/barron-hilton-dead/index.html|title=Barron Hilton, whose empire included hotels and an NFL team, dies at 91|last=Karimi|first=Faith|date=September 21, 2019|website=CNN|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other==\nHilton was a member of a duck club on [[Venice Island (California)|Venice Island]] in the [[Sacramento \u2013 San Joaquin River Delta]] near [[Stockton, California|Stockton]] in Northern California. Every year he put on a large [[Fourth of July]] fireworks display, attracting thousands of boaters to watch it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sports/the-52/sdut-the52-barron-hilton-chargers-2014oct06-htmlstory.html|title=Barron Hilton key to AFL-NFL merger|date=October 6, 2014|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=April 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402143056/https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sports/the-52/sdut-the52-barron-hilton-chargers-2014oct06-htmlstory.html|archive-date=April 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hilton and several friends purchased the [[Flying-M Ranch]] in [[Lyon County, Nevada]] in the mid-1960s, and he bought the others out in 1972.<ref>Freeze, Di (2013). \"In the Cockpit with Barron Hilton\". Freeze Time Media, p. 18</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of American Football League players]]\n* [[Los Angeles Chargers Hall of Fame]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Los Angeles Chargers owner navbox}}\n{{Foolish Club}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hilton, Barron}}\n[[Category:American hoteliers]]\n[[Category:Conrad Hilton family]]\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American investors]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Norwegian descent]]\n[[Category:American real estate businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American socialites]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Texas]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in the drink industry]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Hilton Worldwide]]\n[[Category:Members of the Foolish Club]]\n[[Category:People from Bel Air, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Dallas]]\n[[Category:San Diego Chargers owners]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Chargers owners]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Holmby Hills, Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American hotelier}}\n{{for|the peerage title|Baron Hylton}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| birth_name         = William Barron Hilton\n| name               = Barron Hilton\n| image              = Barron Hilton.JPEG\n| caption            = Barron Hilton in 2007\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|mf=yes|1927|10|23}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dallas, Texas]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2019|9|19|1927|10|23}}\n| death_place        = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| father             = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Southern California]] Aeronautical School\n| occupation         = [[Business]] [[magnate]], [[philanthropist]] and sportsman\n| net_worth          = US$3.4 billion<ref name=\"McNulty 2019\">{{cite web | last=McNulty | first=Matthew | title=Barron Hilton leaves 97% of massive fortune to this foundation | website=Fox Business | date=September 22, 2019 | url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/business-leaders/barron-hilton-fortune-estate-foundation | access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n| spouse             = Marilyn June Hawley (1947\u20132004)\n| children           = 8\n| parents            = {{plain list|\n* [[Conrad Nicholson Hilton]]\n* Mary Adelaide Hilton\n}}\n| relatives          = {{plain list|\n* [[Conrad Nicholson Hilton, Jr.]]  {{small|(brother)}}\n* [[Eric Hilton|Eric Michael Hilton]] {{small|(brother)}}\n* [[Francesca Hilton]] {{small|(half-sister)}}\n* [[Paris Hilton]] {{small|(granddaughter)}}\n* [[Nicky Hilton Rothschild]] {{small|(granddaughter)}}\n}}\n| signature          = Barron_Hilton_Signature.png\n}}\n'''William Barron Hilton''' (October 23, 1927 \u2013 September 19, 2019) was an American [[business magnate]], philanthropist and sportsman. The second son and successor of hotelier [[Conrad Hilton]], he was the chairman, president and chief executive officer of [[Hilton Hotels Corporation]] and chairman emeritus of the [[Conrad N. Hilton Foundation]]. Hilton, a notable pilot and outdoorsman, was also a founder of the [[American Football League]] as the original owner of the [[Los Angeles Chargers]], and helped forge the merger with the [[National Football League]] that created the [[Super Bowl]]. Like his father before him, he pledged 97 percent of his wealth to the humanitarian work of the [[Conrad N. Hilton Foundation]].<ref>\"Barron Hilton to Donate 97% of Estate to Hilton Foundation\". Planned Giving Design Center, LLC. December 26, 2007. Retrieved April 2, 2011.</ref> At the time, the gift was projected to increase the foundation's endowment from $2.9 billion to $6.3 billion,<ref>Haggerty, James R., \"Hilton Founder's Son Sought His Own Path,\" ''Wall Street Journal'', 2019-9-21, p. A6</ref> and will make his estate the organization's most significant donor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hiltonfoundation.org/news/453-conrad-n-hilton-foundation-announces-the-death-of-barron-hilton|title=Conrad N. Hilton Foundation Announces the Death of Barron Hilton|first=Conrad N. Hilton|last=Foundation 818.851.3700|website=Conrad N. Hilton Foundation|accessdate=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nHilton was born in [[Dallas]], [[Texas]], to Mary Adelaide (n\u00e9e Barron) and [[Conrad Hilton|Conrad Nicholson Hilton]], founder of [[Hilton Hotels]]. Hilton grew up with three siblings, [[Conrad Hilton, Jr.|Conrad Nicholson Hilton, Jr.]], Eric Michael Hilton, and Constance Francesca Hilton. His father was of Norwegian and German descent, and his mother was from Kentucky.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wargs.com/other/hilton.html |title=Ancestry of Paris Hilton |publisher=Wargs.com (blog) |date=<!--undated--> |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605185352/http://www.wargs.com/other/hilton.html |archive-date=June 5, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHe served in the [[United States Navy|Navy]] during [[World War II]] as a photographer. As a child, Hilton was fascinated by aviation, and learned to fly when he was 17. After his wartime discharge, he attended the [[University of Southern California]] Aeronautical School, where he earned his [[twin-engine]] rating at age 19.<ref>{{cite web |last=Robertson |first=Cliff |title=Smashing Stereotypes |publisher=Airport Journals |date=June 2006 |url=http://www.airportjournals.com/Display.cfm?varID=0606003 |accessdate=April 3, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717065651/http://www.airportjournals.com/Display.cfm?varID=0606003 |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Early career, Los Angeles Chargers ==\nBefore joining his father in the hotel industry, Barron Hilton honed his business skills in a variety of entrepreneurial ventures. He acquired the Los Angeles-area distributorship of Vita-Pakt Citrus Products, co-founded MacDonald Oil Company, and founded Air Finance Corporation, one of the nation's first aircraft leasing businesses. In 1954, Barron was elected vice president of Hilton Hotels, running the company's franchise operations and creating the [[Carte Blanche (credit card)|Carte Blanche]] credit card as a service to the company's customers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hrm.uh.edu/inductee/inductee.asp?InducteeId=52&id= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326065330/http://www.hrm.uh.edu/inductee/inductee.asp?InducteeId=52&id= |title=Hospitality Hall of Honor \u2013 Inductees \u2013 Barron Hilton |website=[[University of Houston]] |date=<!--undated--> |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |archive-date=March 26, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1959, [[Lamar Hunt]] offered Hilton the Los Angeles franchise in the new [[American Football League]] (AFL). Hilton named his team the [[Chargers]], but denied that he did it to create synergy with his new credit card business. A fan had nominated the name in a contest, and Hilton selected it because of the bugle call and \"Charge!\" cheer that was often sounded during [[USC Trojans football|USC football]] games at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]]. The Chargers began playing at the Coliseum in 1960, but in spite of winning the [[Western Division (NFL)|Western Division]], the club found it difficult to compete for fans with the [[Los Angeles Rams|Rams]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL) in their own stadium. Hilton moved the team to San Diego in time for the [[1961 NFL season|1961 season]] and played in tiny [[Balboa Stadium]], which the city had expanded to 30,000 seats.<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/nov/30/sports/la-sp-dwyre30-2009nov30 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Bill |last=Dwyre |title=Barron Hilton's Chargers turned short stay into long-term success |date=November 30, 2009 |access-date=December 13, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107195724/http://articles.latimes.com/2009/nov/30/sports/la-sp-dwyre30-2009nov30 |archive-date=January 7, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHilton began working with the local newspapers to engender support for construction of a state-of-the-art stadium. Encouraged by [[San Diego Union]] sports editor [[Jack Murphy (sportswriter)|Jack Murphy]], among others, a referendum was passed in 1965, and the Chargers began play in the new San Diego Stadium in 1967. With the availability of a new stadium, the city received a baseball expansion franchise from the National League, and the [[San Diego Padres]] began play in 1969. It was named Jack Murphy Stadium after Murphy's death in 1980, and is now known as [[SDCCU Stadium]].<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\" />\n\nHilton also served as AFL president in 1965, and helped forge the merger between the AFL and the NFL, announced in 1966, which created the Super Bowl. In all, the Chargers won five divisional titles, and one [[AFL Championship]], during Hilton's six years at the helm of the club. In 1966, directors of Hilton Hotels Corporation asked Hilton to succeed his father as president and chief executive officer of the company, provided that he drop his football responsibilities. He sold his majority interest in the team for $10 million\u2014a record for any professional sports franchise at the time\u2014after an initial investment in a franchise fee of just $25,000.<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\" />\n\nWith the death of the Bills' [[Ralph Wilson]] in 2014, Hilton became the last surviving member of the [[Foolish Club]]\u2014the nickname the original AFL owners gave each other, as they absorbed the start-up expenses and player salaries necessary to compete with the established NFL.<ref name = NYTObit/>\n\n==Hilton Hotels==\nOnce charged with the responsibility for Hilton Hotels Corporation, Barron Hilton soon showed his father's genius for cost controls and real estate deals. In 1970, he convinced the board to expand into [[Las Vegas]] by purchasing the International and the Flamingo from financier [[Kirk Kerkorian]]. Hilton Hotels thus became the first company listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] to venture into the gaming market. Renamed the [[Las Vegas Hilton]] and the [[Flamingo Hilton]], the two resorts tapped a new source of income from gambling in a state where it had been legal since 1931. Barron could also see that Las Vegas would become a leading convention destination, capitalizing on the company's strength in that important market segment.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1970 Annual Report, pp. 12\u201316</ref>\n\nHilton personally introduced two innovations that have become standard features of casinos everywhere. Calling on his background in photography, he installed video cameras throughout the casinos to replace the \"eye in the sky\" system of observers peering through two-way mirrors in the ceiling.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pregame.com/sample_weblogs/b/bob-majors/archive/2008/09/07/old-school-las-vegas-then-las-vegas-now-as-perceived-by-bob-majors.aspx |title=Old School \u2013 Las Vegas Then/Las Vegas Now as perceived by Bob Majors \u2013 Bob Majors \u2013 Sample Weblogs |publisher=Pregame.com |date=September 7, 2008 |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |first=Bob |last=Majors |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528200436/http://pregame.com/sample_weblogs/b/bob-majors/archive/2008/09/07/old-school-las-vegas-then-las-vegas-now-as-perceived-by-bob-majors.aspx |archivedate=May 28, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nLas Vegas would also become the self-proclaimed \"Entertainment Capital of the World\". Of all the headliners to perform at the Hilton or the Flamingo, the most successful and spectacular was [[Elvis Presley]]. After a decade in the movies, he began performing in front of live audiences again in 1969 at the opening of the International (a few years later renamed the Las Vegas Hilton). He went on to star at the Las Vegas Hilton two months a year\u2014performing two shows a night, seven nights a week\u2014until shortly before his death in 1977. Presley set a world entertainment record at the Las Vegas Hilton for selling out 837 consecutive concerts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/news/2012/dec/13/25-greatest-headliners-las-vegas-history/ |title=The 25 greatest headliners in Las Vegas history |publisher=Las Vegas Weekly |date=December 13, 2012 |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607190605/http://lasvegasweekly.com/news/2012/dec/13/25-greatest-headliners-las-vegas-history/ |archive-date=June 7, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe company's expansion into Nevada had an immediate impact on its net income. By 1972, the two resorts contributed 45 percent of the company's income (before interest income, interest expense, write down of investments and sales of properties), nearly matching the income from the other 160 Hilton hotels in the United States.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1973 Annual Report, p. 2</ref>\n\nOn the hotel front, in 1975, Hilton sold a 50 percent interest in six of the company's largest hotels to [[Prudential Insurance Company]] for $83 million. He took a [[leaseback]] to manage the properties, collecting lucrative management fees and a percentage of their gross profits. Perhaps more importantly, the sale proved that these hotels were worth double their book value, demonstrating the underlying value of the company's real estate holdings.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1976 Annual Report, p. 5</ref>  The transaction also enhanced the value of the stock held by every HHC shareholder. Hilton used the proceeds to pay down high interest debt, and repurchase 20 percent of the company's stock\u2014all at [[market rate]]\u2014which was still trading well below the company's book value.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1975 Annual Report, p. 4</ref>\n\nHilton continued to expand the domestic hotel chain through franchising and the selective acquisition of management contracts and hotels in emerging markets. In 1977, he completed a hotel purchase that his father had initiated 28 years earlier. When Conrad Hilton bought the [[Waldorf-Astoria]] in 1949, he actually bought the hotel's operating company and its 30-year lease to run the hotel. The building, and the land under it, were still owned by the realty arm of the [[Penn Central Railroad]]. Knowing that the lease would expire in 1979, Hilton deftly negotiated to buy the hotel and real estate from the railroad. The landmark property, whose current value is estimated around $1 billion, was purchased by Hilton for just $35 million.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1976 Annual Report, p. 3</ref> \n\t\nAs competitors aggressively spread across the U.S. in the '80s, Barron held his own by rehabbing his own hotels and increasing revenues in Las Vegas. Through a series of massive additions to the Flamingo Hilton and the Las Vegas Hilton, the company nearly tripled its rooms in Las Vegas by 1990, from 2,277 to 6,703. He also launched Conrad International in the '80s,<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1990 Annual Report, p. 7</ref> and [[Hilton Garden Inn]] in the '90s.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1996 Annual Report, p. 5</ref>\n\nIn contrast to his gamble on gaming, Hilton earned a well-deserved reputation as a financial conservative. After seeing his father struggle to overcome the effects of the [[American Great Depression]] and [[World War II]], he maintained the strongest [[balance sheet]] in the industry. Throughout his 30 years as CEO, he carried a low [[debt-to-capital ratio]] and a high [[credit rating]], enabling him to gobble up such properties as [[Bally's Reno]] (formerly the MGM Grand Hotel and Casino-Reno). The 2,000-room resort was opened in 1978 for $230 million, and purchased by Hilton in 1992 for $88 million. With strong [[cash flow]] and plenty of liquid investments on hand, he was able to weather the inevitable recessions and business interruptions that struck the industry from the mid-'60s to the mid-'90s.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation 1992 Annual Report, pp. 3\u20134</ref>\n \nHilton continued as chairman of the board through the next decade as his hand-picked successor, [[Steve Bollenbach]], dramatically expanded the company through a series of mergers and acquisitions. The advent of friendly capital markets in the late '90s enabled him to acquire such popular brands as [[Embassy Suites]], [[Doubletree]], [[Hampton Inn]], [[Homewood Suites]], Bally's and Caesars.<ref>Hilton Hotels Corporation, 1999 Annual Report, p. 2</ref>  Then, in 2005, he reacquired Hilton International, 38 years after it had been sold to TWA. With the company now strategically complete, Bollenbach spun off the gaming business, which merged with Harrah's in 2005 and was renamed [[Caesars Entertainment Corporation|Caesars Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.webpronews.com/caesars-and-harrahs-to-merge-2005-03 |title=Caesars and Harrah's To Merge |publisher=WebProNews.com |date=March 11, 2005 |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217224227/http://www.webpronews.com/caesars-and-harrahs-to-merge-2005-03 |archive-date=December 17, 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the meantime, the hotel business continued to soar. With the best known and most respected name in the industry\u2014and popular domestic brands ripe for expansion overseas\u2014Hilton Hotels Corporation proved to be irresistible to [[The Blackstone Group]]. In 2007, the private equity firm purchased Hilton Hotels Corporation, consisting of 2,800 hotels with 480,000 rooms in 76 countries and territories. Blackstone paid $47.50 per share, a 32 percent premium over the July 2 closing price. The $26 billion, all-cash transaction included $7.5 billion of debt.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blackstone.com/news-views/press-releases/hilton-hotels-corporation-to-be-acquired-by-blackstone-investments-funds |title=Hilton Hotels Corporation to be Acquired by Blackstone Investments Funds |publisher=Blackstone.com |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528221158/http://www.blackstone.com/news-views/press-releases/hilton-hotels-corporation-to-be-acquired-by-blackstone-investments-funds |archive-date=May 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Host Hotels & Resorts]] veteran Chris Nassetta was hired to manage the company, which was renamed [[Hilton Worldwide]], Inc. and is now known as Hilton, Inc. Now celebrating the 100th year since Conrad Hilton purchased his first hotel, the company has expanded to include 17 brands, 5,800 hotels, and 939,000 rooms in 114 countries of the world.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hilton.com/en/corporate/ |title=Hilton Brands &#124; Global Hospitality Company |access-date=September 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903041043/https://www.hilton.com/en/corporate/ |archive-date=September 3, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> With another 373,000 rooms in the development pipeline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsroom.hilton.com/corporate/news/hilton-reports-second-quarter-results-exceeds-net-income-and-adjusted-ebitda-expectations|title=Hilton Reports Second Quarter Results; Exceeds Net Income and Adjusted EBITDA Expectations|website=Hilton Press Center|accessdate=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Hilton family fortune ==\nIn 1979, Barron Hilton's father, [[Conrad Hilton]], died at age 91. He left 13.5 million shares of Hilton Hotels Corporation stock\u201497 percent of his estate\u2014to the [[Conrad N. Hilton Foundation]], a humanitarian charity which he had established in 1944.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia: Barron Hilton\">{{cite encyclopedia |title=Hilton, William \u2013 Overview, Personal Life, Career Details, Social and Economic Impact, Chronology: Hilton, William |publisher=Net Industries |url=http://encyclopedia.jrank.org/articles/pages/6273/Hilton-William.html |format=Encyclopedia |accessdate=April 2, 2011 |date=<!--undated--> |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215163811/http://encyclopedia.jrank.org/articles/pages/6273/Hilton-William.html |archivedate=February 15, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn his will, Conrad also gave Barron the right to purchase those shares in order to maintain family control of the company, but the foundation challenged the option in [[probate court]]. It took an entire decade to resolve the issue. Hilton's right to exercise his option was upheld in an appeals court ruling in March 1988, giving him [[Voting interest|voting power]] over roughly 34 percent of the company's [[Outstanding Shares|outstanding shares]]. Conrad's bequest of stock was worth $160 million when he died in 1979. Thanks to his son's successful management of the Hilton Hotels Corporation, those shares were worth $654 million when the settlement was reached late in 1988. In a press statement issued after the favorable ruling, Hilton said it gave him \"the opportunity to structure an arrangement whereby my father's two objectives, retaining control of the stock in family hands, and benefiting charity through the Conrad N. Hilton Foundation, can both be achieved. I am confident that my father would be pleased with this accord.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-11-26/business/fi-240_1_barron-hilton |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |first=Al |last=Delugach |title=Barron Hilton Wins Battle for Chain : Settlement of Lengthy Dispute Gives Hotelier Effective Control |date=November 26, 1988 |access-date=December 13, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218125601/http://articles.latimes.com/1988-11-26/business/fi-240_1_barron-hilton |archive-date=December 18, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe settlement was finalized in 1989. Neither Hilton, nor the foundation, had to actually pay for the shares; they split them instead. Hilton received 4 million shares, the Conrad N. Hilton Foundation received 3.5 million shares, and the remaining 6 million shares were placed in the W. Barron Hilton [[Charitable remainder unitrust|Charitable Remainder Unitrust]], of which Barron was the executor. He received 60 percent of the unitrust income, and the foundation 40 percent, during his lifetime, then the fund would transfer to the foundation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-05-12/business/fi-2998_1_barron-hilton-founder-s-estate-conrad-n-hilton-foundation |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |first=Al |last=Delugach |title=Hilton Open to Offers but No Deal Pending, CEO Says |date=May 12, 1989 |access-date=December 13, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218125604/http://articles.latimes.com/1989-05-12/business/fi-2998_1_barron-hilton-founder-s-estate-conrad-n-hilton-foundation |archive-date=December 18, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn December 25, 2007, Hilton announced that he would follow in his father's footsteps by leaving about 97 percent of his estate, estimated at that time to be $2.3 billion, to the [[Conrad N. Hilton Foundation]].<ref name=\"PGDC\">{{cite web |title=Barron Hilton to Donate 97% of Estate to Hilton Foundation |date=December 26, 2007 |publisher=Planned Giving Design Center, LLC |url=http://www.pgdc.com/pgdc/news-story/2007/12/27/barron-hilton-donate-97-estate-hilton-foundation |accessdate=April 2, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319015235/http://www.pgdc.com/pgdc/news-story/2007/12/27/barron-hilton-donate-97-estate-hilton-foundation |archive-date=March 19, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7161358.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |title=Hilton fortune to go to charity |date=December 27, 2007 |accessdate=April 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206182754/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7161358.stm |archive-date=December 6, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> Included was an immediate pledge of $1.2 billion, the proceeds of the sale of Hilton Hotels Corporation and Harrah's Entertainment Inc., which was placed in a [[charitable remainder unitrust]] that would be transferred to the foundation upon Hilton's death at whatever value the trust was worth at that time.<ref name=\"PGDC\"/><ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-12-26-hilton-donate_N.htm |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |title=Hilton to donate bulk of fortune to foundation |date=December 27, 2007 |accessdate=April 2, 2011 |first=Roger |last=Yu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530163049/http://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-12-26-hilton-donate_N.htm |archive-date=May 30, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The remainder of the funds that constitute Hilton's pledge of 97 percent of his estate will come from his personal assets, which were estimated at $1.1 billion at the time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/30/business/30suits.html|title=A Hilton in the News (and It's Not Paris)|last=Olson|first=Elizabeth|date=December 30, 2007|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 2, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402143623/https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/30/business/30suits.html|archive-date=April 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Conrad N. Hilton Foundation==\nThroughout his career, Conrad Hilton supported a variety of causes, particularly those involving the nuns that had helped educate him in his native [[New Mexico]]. He established the [[Conrad N. Hilton Foundation]] in 1944, and made a total of $7.6 million of gifts before his death.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hiltonfoundation.org/about/history |title=History |website=Hiltonfoundation.org |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107195726/https://www.hiltonfoundation.org/about/history |archive-date=January 7, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn his last will and testament, Conrad left general guidance for the use of his endowment. He wrote: \"There is a natural law, a Divine law, that obliges you and me to relieve the suffering, the distressed and the destitute. Charity is a supreme virtue, and the great channel through which the mercy of God is passed on to mankind. It is the virtue that unites men and inspires their noblest efforts. 'Love one another, for that is the whole law;' so our fellow men deserve to be loved and encouraged\u2014never abandoned to wander alone in poverty and darkness. The practice of charity will bind us\u2014will bind all men in one great brotherhood. As the funds you will expend have come from many places in the world, so let there be no territorial, religious, or color restrictions on your benefactions, but beware of organized, professional charities with high-salaried executives and a heavy ratio of expense. Be ever watchful for the opportunity to shelter little children with the umbrella of your charity; be generous to their schools, their hospitals and their places of worship. For, as they must bear the burdens of our mistakes, so are they in their innocence the repositories of our hopes for the upward progress of humanity. Give aid to their protectors and defenders, the Sisters, who devote their love and life's work for the good of mankind, for they appeal especially to me as being deserving of help from the Foundation.\"<ref>[http://hiltonfoundation.org/last-will ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527043302/http://hiltonfoundation.org/last-will |date=May 27, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Aviation career==\nHilton was born the year [[Charles Lindbergh]] flew the [[Spirit of St. Louis]] across the Atlantic. When he was 7 or 8 years old, he would ride his bike to [[Dallas Love Field|Love Field]] in [[Dallas]] to watch the exotic planes of the day take off and land. He promised himself that he would one day learn to fly. He took private flying lessons at a field on the north shore of Oahu during his time in the Navy, and got his pilot's license at age 17.<ref name=\"airportjournals.com\">[http://www.airportjournals.com/Display.cfm?varID=0307003 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120627093532/http://www.airportjournals.com/Display.cfm?varID=0307003 |date=June 27, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his single-engine and multi-engine ratings, Hilton eventually earned glider, lighter than air (balloons) and helicopter ratings as well. He maintained a small fleet of aircraft at his [[Flying-M Ranch|Flying M Ranch]] east of the sierras in northern Nevada that includes sailplanes, tow planes, aerobatic aircraft, hot air balloons and classic, restored biplanes.<ref name=\"airportjournals.com\"/>  He flew them all until he retired from the cockpit in 2012 at age 84.<ref>{{cite book |last=Freeze |first=Di |title=In the Cockpit with Barron Hilton |year=2013 |page=xv |isbn=978-0985810368}}</ref>\n\nIn the '90s, he boldly backed the first attempts to capture one of the last great milestones in aviation\u2014flying non-stop around the world in a balloon\u2014with the Earthwinds Hilton and Global Hilton campaigns. While falling short of the ultimate goal, Hilton is credited with inspiring the efforts of those who achieved the feat. [[Bertrand Piccard]] and [[Brian Jones]] were the first to make a trans-global flight in 1999; [[Steve Fossett]] became the first to complete the flight solo in 2002.<ref name=\"airportjournals.com\"/>\n\nFrom 1980 to 2009, he also hosted the [[Barron Hilton Cup]], a unique, worldwide glider competition. Pilots who flew the longest triangular flights during each two-year period in six regions of the world earned participation in a weeklong soaring camp at his Flying M Ranch. Co-founder [[Helmut Reichmann]], Germany's three-time world soaring champion, devised a handicap system that enabled pilots flying older gliders to compete with elite pilots in high-performance aircraft of the latest design. Once at the Flying M, they flew recreationally alongside world champions and celebrities invited to attend by Hilton. Beginning in 1996 with its predecessors, the European Aeronautic Defence and Space Co., [[EADS]], had served as a partner in the event.<ref name=\"airportjournals.com\"/>\n\nOver the years, a number of notable pilots regularly joined Hilton for weekends at the Flying M. They include entertainers [[John Denver]] and [[Cliff Robertson]]; astronauts [[Neil Armstrong]], [[Gene Cernan]], [[Bill Anders]], and [[Ulf Merbold]]; and test pilots and record-holders Johnny Myers, [[Clay Lacy]], Bruno Gantenbrink, [[Bob Hoover]], [[Carroll Shelby]], Sully Sullenberger, and air, sea and land adventurer, [[Steve Fossett]].<ref name=\"airportjournals.com\"/>\n\nOn Labor Day, 2007, Fossett took off from the Flying M Ranch and never returned, perishing in a crash in the Sierras. In spite of an intensive search, the wreckage wasn't discovered until the following spring. The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause(s) of this accident to be \"the pilot's inadvertent encounter with downdrafts that exceeded the climb capability of the airplane. Contributing to the accident were the downdrafts, high density altitude, and mountainous terrain.\"  Examination of the airframe and engine revealed no evidence of any malfunctions or failures that would have prevented normal operation.<ref>[http://www.ntsb.gov/aviationquery/brief.aspx?ev_id=20081007X17184&key=1 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203023400/http://www.ntsb.gov/aviationquery/brief.aspx?ev_id=20081007X17184&key=1 |date=December 3, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Smithsonian National Air & Space Museum]] honored Hilton in 2010 by christening the Barron Hilton Pioneers of Flight Gallery. The redesigned exhibit recognizes aviators like Lindbergh, [[Amelia Earhart]] and the [[Tuskeegee Airmen]]. The gallery includes an early childhood education component funded by the Hilton Foundation to help youngsters catch the same enthusiasm for aviation that he discovered as a child when Lindbergh and Earhart were making headlines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsdesk.si.edu/releases/barron-hilton-pioneers-flight-gallery-opens-nov-19 |title=\"Barron Hilton Pioneers of Flight Gallery\" Opens Nov. 19 &#124; Newsdesk |publisher=Newsdesk.si.edu |date=November 16, 2010 |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528201234/http://newsdesk.si.edu/releases/barron-hilton-pioneers-flight-gallery-opens-nov-19 |archive-date=May 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Barron was inducted into the [[International Air & Space Hall of Fame]] at the [[San Diego Air & Space Museum]].<ref>Sprekelmeyer, Linda, editor. ''These We Honor: The International Aerospace Hall of Fame''. Donning Co. Publishers, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1-57864-397-4}}.</ref>\n\nFor his lifelong support of aviation, Hilton received the prestigious [[FAI Gold Air Medal]] from the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration A\u00e9ronautique Internationale]] in 2009, the same award bestowed upon some of his closest friends and personal heroes, like Yeager, Armstrong, Cernan, Jones, Fossett, and Lindbergh himself.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fai.org/awards/fai-general-awards |title=General Awards |publisher=Fai.org |date=July 5, 2011 |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420212845/http://www.fai.org/awards/fai-general-awards |archivedate=April 20, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Hilton was also inducted into the International Air & Space Hall of Fame in San Diego, and was hailed as the \"patron saint of sport aviation.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sandiegoairandspace.org/press/release.php?id=60 |title=San Diego Air & Space Museum \u2013 Balboa Park, San Diego |publisher=Sandiegoairandspace.org |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528200331/http://www.sandiegoairandspace.org/press/release.php?id=60 |archive-date=May 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1947, Barron Hilton married Marilyn June Hawley; they remained married until she died in 2004. They had eight children: William Barron Hilton, Jr.; Hawley Anne Hilton; [[Steven M. Hilton|Stephen Michael Hilton]]; David Alan Hilton; Sharon Constance Hilton; [[Richard Hilton|Richard Howard Hilton]]; Daniel Kevin Hilton; and Ronald Jeffrey Hilton; William Barron Hilton, Jr. was born in 1948 and Ronald Jeffrey Hilton was born in 1963. Barron Hilton had 15 grandchildren, including Richard Hilton's daughters [[Paris Hilton]] and [[Nicky Hilton Rothschild]], and four great-grandchildren. \n\nHis primary residence in [[Holmby Hills, Los Angeles|Holmby Hills]] was the [[Jay Paley House]], originally designed in the 1930s for Jay Paley<ref>{{Citation | title = Jay Paley Residence | work = Paul Revere Williams Project Gallery | year = 2010 | url = http://www.paulrwilliamsproject.org/gallery/1930s-houses/ | access-date = March 3, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100503160046/http://www.paulrwilliamsproject.org/gallery/1930s-houses | archive-date = May 3, 2010 | url-status = live }}</ref> by architect [[Paul Williams (architect)|Paul Williams]]. It was used as the 'Colby mansion' in exterior scenes for ''[[The Colbys]]'' television series. He also maintained a permanent suite in New York\u2019s Waldorf, and a 475,000-acre ranch called ''Flying M'' stretching across Nevada & California state lines. The ranch included an airport and a two-hole putting green.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lester |first=Peter |date=28 Sep 1981 |title=When This Hotel Barron Says He's Staying at the Hilton, That Means He'll Be at Home |url=https://people.com/archive/when-this-hotel-barron-says-hes-staying-at-the-hilton-that-means-hell-be-at-home-vol-16-no-13/ |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |access-date=8 Apr 2020}}</ref>\n\nHilton died of natural causes at his home in Los Angeles on September 19, 2019.<ref name = NYTObit>{{cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/business/barron-hilton-dead.html|title = Barron Hilton, Hotel Magnate and Founding A.F.L. Owner, Dies at 91|last = Goldstein|first = Richard|date = September 20, 2019|accessdate = September 22, 2019|work = [[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Karimi 2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/21/entertainment/barron-hilton-dead/index.html|title=Barron Hilton, whose empire included hotels and an NFL team, dies at 91|last=Karimi|first=Faith|date=September 21, 2019|website=CNN|access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other==\nHilton was a member of a duck club on [[Venice Island (California)|Venice Island]] in the [[Sacramento \u2013 San Joaquin River Delta]] near [[Stockton, California|Stockton]] in Northern California. Every year he put on a large [[Fourth of July]] fireworks display, attracting thousands of boaters to watch it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sports/the-52/sdut-the52-barron-hilton-chargers-2014oct06-htmlstory.html|title=Barron Hilton key to AFL-NFL merger|date=October 6, 2014|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=April 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402143056/https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sports/the-52/sdut-the52-barron-hilton-chargers-2014oct06-htmlstory.html|archive-date=April 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hilton and several friends purchased the [[Flying-M Ranch]] in [[Lyon County, Nevada]] in the mid-1960s, and he bought the others out in 1972.<ref>Freeze, Di (2013). \"In the Cockpit with Barron Hilton\". Freeze Time Media, p. 18</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of American Football League players]]\n* [[Los Angeles Chargers Hall of Fame]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Los Angeles Chargers owner navbox}}\n{{Foolish Club}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hilton, Barron}}\n[[Category:American hoteliers]]\n[[Category:Conrad Hilton family]]\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American investors]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Norwegian descent]]\n[[Category:American real estate businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American socialites]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Texas]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in the drink industry]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Hilton Worldwide]]\n[[Category:Members of the Foolish Club]]\n[[Category:People from Bel Air, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from Dallas]]\n[[Category:San Diego Chargers owners]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Chargers owners]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Holmby Hills, Los Angeles]]\n", "name_user": "Fylindfotberserk", "label": "safe", "comment": "Generalformattingbyscript;WP:DONOTFIXIT", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barron_Hilton"}
{"title_page": "Babbitt, North Bergen", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Babbitt, North Bergen\n|settlement_type          = [[Local government in New Jersey#Unincorporated communities|Unincorporated community]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map              = USA New Jersey Hudson County\n|pushpin_label_position   = left\n|pushpin_map_caption      = \n|pushpin_map1             = \n|pushpin_label_position1  = \n|pushpin_map_caption1     = \n|pushpin_mapsize          = \n|image_map                = \n|map_caption              =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of countries|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[New Jersey]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in New Jersey|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Hudson County, New Jersey|Hudson]]\n|subdivision_type3        = [[List of townships in New Jersey|Township]]\n|subdivision_name3        = [[North Bergen, New Jersey|North Bergen]]\n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = \n|utc_offset               = \n|timezone_DST             = \n|utc_offset_DST           = \n|elevation_footnotes      = <ref name=GNIS/>\n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             = 10\n|coordinates              = {{coord|40|48|35|N|74|01|12|W|region:US-NJ_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type         = \n|postal_code              = \n|area_code                = \n|blank_name               = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank_info               = 874439<ref name=GNIS>{{cite gnis|874439|Babbitt}}</ref>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n|unit_pref                = imperial\n}}\n'''Babbitt''' is a neighborhood in [[North Bergen, New Jersey|North Bergen Township]] in [[Hudson County, New Jersey|Hudson County]], [[New Jersey]], United States.<ref>[http://www.state.nj.us/infobank/localnames.txt Locality Search] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709092825/http://www.state.nj.us/infobank/localnames.txt |date=July 9, 2016 }}, State of New Jersey. Accessed February 7, 2015.</ref> The area, located west of [[Tonnelle Avenue]] within the [[New Jersey Meadowlands|New Jersey Meadowlands District]], is home to [[light manufacturing]], [[warehouse]]s, transportation facilities, and part of the [[wetlands]] preservation area known as the Eastern Brackish Marsh.<ref>{{cite web   | title = USGS Map Name:Weehawken, NJ Map MRC: 40074G1   | work =    | publisher = TopoQuest   | date =    | url = http://www.topoquest.com/map.php?lat=40.80982&lon=-74.01986&datum=nad83&zoom=4&map=auto&coord=d&mode=zoomin&size=m   | accessdate = September 30, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web   | title = Eastern Brackish Marsh   | work =    | publisher = New Jersey Meadowlands Commission   | url = http://meri.njmeadowlands.gov/mesic/sites/existing-restoration-preservation-mitigation-sites/eastern-brackish-marsh-2/   | accessdate = September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Babbitt's Best Soap==\nThe name is taken from the company that produced ''Babbitt's Best Soap'', named after its founder, [[Benjamin T. Babbitt]]. In 1904 the company purchased a tract of {{convert|87|acre|ha}} between Granton and [[Fairview, Bergen County, New Jersey|Faiview]],<ref>{{cite news   | title = To Abandon Down-Town Factory Site   | publisher = The New York Times   | date = June 12, 1904   | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1909/05/25/101738637.pdf   | accessdate = September 30, 2013}}</ref> and in 1907 relocated from its former premises, a {{convert|22,000|sqft|m2|lk=in|sigfig=2}} facility on [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]] in [[Lower Manhattan]].<ref>{{cite news   | title = Big Downtown Sale   | publisher = The New York Times   | date = April 17, 2010   | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/04/17/102038271.pdf   | accessdate = September 30, 2013}}</ref> to what was then one of the largest [[soap|soap manufacturing]] plants in the world.<ref>{{cite news   | title = In the Real Estate Field: New Babbitt Plant Mortgaged.   | publisher = The New York Times   | date = November 23, 1907   | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1907/11/23/104999552.pdf   | accessdate = September 30, 2013}}</ref> [[Sinclair Lewis]]'s novel ''[[Babbitt (novel)|Babbitt]]'' about an industrialist used the surname.<ref name=\"grave\">{{cite web |url=\nhttps://www.findagrave.com/memorial/6933515|title=Find a Grave |work=Benjamin T. Babbitt|accessdate=September 7, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Granton Junction and Babbitt station==\n[[File:Babitt(Erie-NYS&W)trackside.png|thumb|left|Station circa 1910]]\n[[File:BabbittNYSWmainline83rd.JPG|thumb|View west to NYSW and Northern Branch at grade crossings and West Shore viaduct at 83rd Street, which is slated for closure if the HBLR extension is built.]]\n[[File:BabbittNorthernBranchRiverLine4.JPG|thumb|The Northern Branch Corridor passes under CSX River Division.]]\nThe [[West Shore Railroad]], the [[Erie Railroad]]'s [[Northern Branch]], and the [[New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway|New York, Susquehanna, and Western]] (NYSW) all passed through the area running parallel to each other.<ref>{{cite web   | title = Appendix H: Historic Properties and Resources   | work = Northern Branch Corridor Project DEIS   | publisher = New Jersey Transit   | date = December 2011   | url = http://www.northernbranchcorridor.com/docs/Northern%20Branch%20DOCS/Northern%20Branch%20DEIS%20Appendices/Appendix%20H%20-%20Historic.pdf   | accessdate = September 30, 2013}}</ref> Both Erie and NYSW maintained minor [[railroad stations|stations]]<ref name=\"codes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jon-n-bevliles.net/RAILROAD/erie_docs/erie-losn16.html|title=List of Station Names and Numbers|date=May 1, 1916|publisher=[[Erie Railroad]]|location=[[Jersey City, New Jersey]]|accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref> nearby 83rd Street, which crossed under the [[right of way (transportation)|right-of-way]] of the West Shore. Granton Junction was located just south of the stations and was where NYSW and Erie converged after the latter had also passed under the West Shore.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Sheppard | first = Bill | title = Granton Junction | journal = The Block Line | volume = V | issue = VIII | date = October 1977 | publisher = National Railway Historical Society (Tri-State Chapter) | url = http://tristaterail.org/documents/theblocklinearchives/BLV05N08%20197710%20Searchable.pdf | access-date = October 2, 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215135/http://tristaterail.org/documents/theblocklinearchives/BLV05N08%20197710%20Searchable.pdf | archive-date = October 4, 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{Citation   | last = Kaminski   | first = Edward S.   | title = New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway in New Jersey | publisher =  Arcadia Publishing | year = 2010 |page = 9 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=G1ENevqcHHcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=NEW+YORK,+SUSQUEHANNA+%26+WESTERN+RAILROAD+IN+NEW+JERSEY&hl=en&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=NEW%20YORK%2C%20SUSQUEHANNA%20%26%20WESTERN%20RAILROAD%20IN%20NEW%20JERSEY&f=false   | isbn = 978-0-7385-7367-0   | quote = }}</ref> For a time Granton was busy [[railroad junction]] used by both the Erie and NYSW, which shared track and stations, including the [[Susquehanna Transfer (NYS&W station)|Susquehanna Transfer]]. The name Granton comes from a former [[quarry]] that later was site of an important fossil find of a [[phytosaur]].<ref>{{cite journal  | last = Colbertz  | first =Edwin  | title = A Phytosaur from North Bergen, New Jersey  | journal = American Museum Novitates  | issue = 2230  | date = September 10, 1965  | publisher = American Museum of Natural History  | url =http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/dspace/bitstream/handle/2246/3324/N2230.pdf?sequence=1  | accessdate = September 30, 2013}}</ref> Joint operations between the Erie and NYSW were controlled by GR Tower, which in 1959 was destroyed by fire, ending the relationship.<ref>{{Citation   | last = Mohowski   | first = Robert E.   | title = New York Susquehanna and Western   | publisher = Johns Hopkins University Press   | year = 2003   | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=c-8VcwgnbOYC&pg=PA172 }}</ref> Originally the soap works were outfitted with rail spurs by the NYSW, but by 1909 they had been removed in a renegade action in which factory workers where locked-up and the tracks removed and hauled away.<ref>{{cite news   | title = Seize Factory Hands Remove Its Track   | newspaper = The New York Times   | date = May 25, 1909   | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1909/05/25/101738637.pdf   | accessdate = September 30, 2013   | quote = }}</ref> In August 1922, a full Sunday evening Erie train heading south to [[Pavonia Terminal]] was struck by bombs thrown at it in what was considered an act of sabotage and an attempt to cause a collision.<ref>{{cite news   | title = Bombs Strike Two Cars   | newspaper = The New York Times   | date = August 14, 1922   | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/08/14/99055771.pdf   | accessdate = September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==CSX and HBLR Northern Branch 91st Street station==\nThe West Shore subsequently became [[Conrail]]'s [[River Line (Conrail)|River Line]], and eventually the [[River Subdivision (CSX Transportation)|CSX River Subdivision]] which begins to the south at [[North Bergen Yard]]. Road access to its [[Little Ferry Yard]] is located in Babbitt.\n\nThe [[Hudson-Bergen Light Rail]] extension into eastern [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen County]] known as the [[Northern Branch Corridor Project]] calls for the closure of the [[at-grade crossing]] at 83rd Street and creation of a new one at 85th Street.<ref>{{cite web   | title = 85th Street at Grade Realignment & Closure of 83rd Street   | work = Northern Branch Corridor   | publisher = New Jersey Transit   | date =    | url = http://www.northernbranchcorridor.com/docs/clcnov07/85thStreet%20Realignment.pdf   | accessdate = September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA [[91st Street (HBLR station)]] is planned.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of neighborhoods in North Bergen, New Jersey]]\n*[[List of New Jersey railroad junctions]]\n*[[Template:NYSW (passenger 1939-1966) map|NYSW (passenger 1939-1966) map]]\n*[[Template:Northern Branch (NJ Transit)|Northern Branch (NJ Transit) map]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Hudson County, New Jersey}}\n\n[[Category:North Bergen, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Hudson County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Hudson County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway]]\n[[Category:CSX Transportation]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Babbitt, North Bergen\n|settlement_type          = [[Local government in New Jersey#Unincorporated communities|Unincorporated community]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map              = USA New Jersey Hudson County\n|pushpin_label_position   = left\n|pushpin_map_caption      = \n|pushpin_map1             = \n|pushpin_label_position1  = \n|pushpin_map_caption1     = \n|pushpin_mapsize          = \n|image_map                = \n|map_caption              =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of countries|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[New Jersey]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in New Jersey|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Hudson County, New Jersey|Hudson]]\n|subdivision_type3        = [[List of townships in New Jersey|Township]]\n|subdivision_name3        = [[North Bergen, New Jersey|North Bergen]]\n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = \n|utc_offset               = \n|timezone_DST             = \n|utc_offset_DST           = \n|elevation_footnotes      = <ref name=GNIS/>\n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             = 10\n|coordinates              = {{coord|40|48|35|N|74|01|12|W|region:US-NJ_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type         = \n|postal_code              = \n|area_code                = \n|blank_name               = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank_info               = 874439<ref name=GNIS>{{cite gnis|874439|Babbitt}}</ref>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n|unit_pref                = imperial\n}}\n'''Babbitt''' is a neighborhood in [[North Bergen, New Jersey|North Bergen Township]] in [[Hudson County, New Jersey|Hudson County]], [[New Jersey]], United States.<ref>[http://www.state.nj.us/infobank/localnames.txt Locality Search] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709092825/http://www.state.nj.us/infobank/localnames.txt |date=2016-07-09 }}, State of New Jersey. Accessed February 7, 2015.</ref> The area, located west of [[Tonnelle Avenue]] within the [[New Jersey Meadowlands|New Jersey Meadowlands District]], is home to [[light manufacturing]], [[warehouse]]s, transportation facilities, and part of the [[wetlands]] preservation area known as the Eastern Brackish Marsh.<ref>{{cite web   | title = USGS Map Name:Weehawken, NJ Map MRC: 40074G1   | work =    | publisher = TopoQuest   | date =    | url = http://www.topoquest.com/map.php?lat=40.80982&lon=-74.01986&datum=nad83&zoom=4&map=auto&coord=d&mode=zoomin&size=m   | accessdate = 2013-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web   | title = Eastern Brackish Marsh   | work =    | publisher = New Jersey Meadowlands Commission   | url = http://meri.njmeadowlands.gov/mesic/sites/existing-restoration-preservation-mitigation-sites/eastern-brackish-marsh-2/   | accessdate = 2013-09-30}}</ref>\n\n==Babbitt's Best Soap==\nThe name is taken from the company that produced ''Babbitt's Best Soap'', named after its founder, [[Benjamin T. Babbitt]]. In 1904 the company purchased a tract of {{convert|87|acre|ha}} between Granton and [[Fairview, Bergen County, New Jersey|Faiview]],<ref>{{cite news   | title = To Abandon Down-Town Factory Site   | publisher = The New York Times   | date = June 12, 1904   | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1909/05/25/101738637.pdf   | accessdate = 2013-09-30}}</ref> and in 1907 relocated from its former premises, a {{convert|22,000|sqft|m2|lk=in|sigfig=2}} facility on [[West Street (Manhattan)|West Street]] in [[Lower Manhattan]].<ref>{{cite news   | title = Big Downtown Sale   | publisher = The New York Times   | date = April 17, 2010   | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/04/17/102038271.pdf   | accessdate = 2013-09-30}}</ref> to what was then one of the largest [[soap|soap manufacturing]] plants in the world.<ref>{{cite news   | title = In the Real Estate Field: New Babbitt Plant Mortgaged.   | publisher = The New York Times   | date = November 23, 1907   | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1907/11/23/104999552.pdf   | accessdate = 2013-09-30}}</ref> [[Sinclair Lewis]]'s novel ''[[Babbitt (novel)|Babbitt]]'' about an industrialist used the surname.<ref name=\"grave\">{{cite web |url=\nhttps://www.findagrave.com/memorial/6933515|title=Find a Grave |work=Benjamin T. Babbitt|accessdate=September 7, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Granton Junction and Babbitt station==\n[[File:Babitt(Erie-NYS&W)trackside.png|thumb|left|Station circa 1910]]\n[[File:BabbittNYSWmainline83rd.JPG|thumb|View west to NYSW and Northern Branch at grade crossings and West Shore viaduct at 83rd Street, which is slated for closure if the HBLR extension is built.]]\n[[File:BabbittNorthernBranchRiverLine4.JPG|thumb|The Northern Branch Corridor passes under CSX River Division.]]\nThe [[West Shore Railroad]], the [[Erie Railroad]]'s [[Northern Branch]], and the [[New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway|New York, Susquehanna, and Western]] (NYSW) all passed through the area running parallel to each other.<ref>{{cite web   | title = Appendix H: Historic Properties and Resources   | work = Northern Branch Corridor Project DEIS   | publisher = New Jersey Transit   | date = December 2011   | url = http://www.northernbranchcorridor.com/docs/Northern%20Branch%20DOCS/Northern%20Branch%20DEIS%20Appendices/Appendix%20H%20-%20Historic.pdf   | accessdate = 2013-09-30}}</ref> Both Erie and NYSW maintained minor [[railroad stations|stations]]<ref name=\"codes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jon-n-bevliles.net/RAILROAD/erie_docs/erie-losn16.html|title=List of Station Names and Numbers|date=May 1, 1916|publisher=[[Erie Railroad]]|location=[[Jersey City, New Jersey]]|accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref> nearby 83rd Street, which crossed under the [[right of way (transportation)|right-of-way]] of the West Shore. Granton Junction was located just south of the stations and was where NYSW and Erie converged after the latter had also passed under the West Shore.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Sheppard | first = Bill | title = Granton Junction | journal = The Block Line | volume = V | issue = VIII | date = October 1977 | publisher = National Railway Historical Society (Tri-State Chapter) | url = http://tristaterail.org/documents/theblocklinearchives/BLV05N08%20197710%20Searchable.pdf | access-date = 2013-10-02 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215135/http://tristaterail.org/documents/theblocklinearchives/BLV05N08%20197710%20Searchable.pdf | archive-date = 2013-10-04 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{Citation   | last = Kaminski   | first = Edward S.   | title = New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway in New Jersey | publisher =  Arcadia Publishing | year = 2010 |page = 9 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=G1ENevqcHHcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=NEW+YORK,+SUSQUEHANNA+%26+WESTERN+RAILROAD+IN+NEW+JERSEY&hl=en&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=NEW%20YORK%2C%20SUSQUEHANNA%20%26%20WESTERN%20RAILROAD%20IN%20NEW%20JERSEY&f=false   | isbn = 978-0-7385-7367-0   | quote = }}</ref> For a time Granton was busy [[railroad junction]] used by both the Erie and NYSW, which shared track and stations, including the [[Susquehanna Transfer (NYS&W station)|Susquehanna Transfer]]. The name Granton comes from a former [[quarry]] that later was site of an important fossil find of a [[phytosaur]].<ref>{{cite journal  | last = Colbertz  | first =Edwin  | title = A Phytosaur from North Bergen, New Jersey  | journal = American Museum Novitates  | issue = 2230  | date = September 10, 1965  | publisher = American Museum of Natural History  | url =http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/dspace/bitstream/handle/2246/3324/N2230.pdf?sequence=1  | accessdate = 2013-09-30}}</ref> Joint operations between the Erie and NYSW were controlled by GR Tower, which in 1959 was destroyed by fire, ending the relationship.<ref>{{Citation   | last = Mohowski   | first = Robert E.   | title = New York Susquehanna and Western   | publisher = Johns Hopkins University Press   | year = 2003   | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=c-8VcwgnbOYC&pg=PA172 }}</ref> Originally the soap works were outfitted with rail spurs by the NYSW, but by 1909 they had been removed in a renegade action in which factory workers where locked-up and the tracks removed and hauled away.<ref>{{cite news   | title = Seize Factory Hands Remove Its Track   | newspaper = The New York Times   | date = May 25, 1909   | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1909/05/25/101738637.pdf   | accessdate = 2013-09-30   | quote = }}</ref> In August 1922, a full Sunday evening Erie train heading south to [[Pavonia Terminal]] was struck by bombs thrown at it in what was considered an act of sabotage and an attempt to cause a collision.<ref>{{cite news   | title = Bombs Strike Two Cars   | newspaper = The New York Times   | date = August 14, 1922   | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/08/14/99055771.pdf   | accessdate = 2013-09-30}}</ref>\n\n==CSX and HBLR Northern Branch 91st Street station==\nThe West Shore subsequently became [[Conrail]]'s [[River Line (Conrail)|River Line]], and eventually the [[River Subdivision (CSX Transportation)|CSX River Subdivision]] which begins to the south at [[North Bergen Yard]]. Road access to its [[Little Ferry Yard]] is located in Babbitt.\n\nThe [[Hudson-Bergen Light Rail]] extension into eastern [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen County]] known as the [[Northern Branch Corridor Project]] calls for the closure of the [[at-grade crossing]] at 83rd Street and creation of a new one at 85th Street.<ref>{{cite web   | title = 85th Street at Grade Realignment & Closure of 83rd Street   | work = Northern Branch Corridor   | publisher = New Jersey Transit   | date =    | url = http://www.northernbranchcorridor.com/docs/clcnov07/85thStreet%20Realignment.pdf   | accessdate = 2013-09-30}}</ref>\n\nA [[91st Street (HBLR station)]] is planned.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of neighborhoods in North Bergen, New Jersey]]\n*[[List of New Jersey railroad junctions]]\n*[[Template:NYSW (passenger 1939-1966) map|NYSW (passenger 1939-1966) map]]\n*[[Template:Northern Branch (NJ Transit)|Northern Branch (NJ Transit) map]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Hudson County, New Jersey}}\n\n[[Category:North Bergen, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Hudson County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Hudson County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway]]\n[[Category:CSX Transportation]]\n", "name_user": "Kew Gardens 613", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Babbitt,_North_Bergen"}
{"title_page": "More About Nostradamus", "text_new": "{{short description|1941 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = More About Nostradamus\n| image          = More about Nostradamus -- screenshot.jpg\n| caption        = Titular screenshot\n| director       = [[David Miller (director)|David Miller]]\n| producer       = [[Carey Wilson (writer)|Carey Wilson]]\n| writer         = [[Carl Dudley]]\n| starring       = [[John Burton (actor)|John Burton]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography = Charles Lawton Jr.\n| editing        = Adrienne Fazan\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{film date|1941|1|18}}\n| runtime        = 11 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''More About Nostradamus''''' is a 1941 American [[short film]] directed by [[David Miller (director)|David Miller]]. In 1941 it was nominated for an [[Academy Award]] at the [[13th Academy Awards]] for [[Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film|Best Live Action Short Film, One-Reel]].<ref name=\"Oscars1941\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1941 |title=The 13th Academy Awards (1941) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=August 12, 2011|work=oscars.org| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110706093728/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/13th-winners.html| archivedate= July 6, 2011 <!--Added by DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/300670/More-About-Nostradamus/details |title=New York Times: More About Nostradamus |accessdate=November 29, 2010 |work=NY Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103102057/http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/300670/More-About-Nostradamus/details |archive-date=November 3, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[John Burton (actor)|John Burton]] as [[Nostradamus|Michel de Nostradamus]]\n* [[Hans Conried]] as Feliz Paretti later [[Pope Sixtus V]]\n* [[James Dime]] as Grave Digger\n* [[John George (actor)|John George]] as Townsman\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0032810|title=More About Nostradamus}}\n\n{{David Miller}}\n{{Nostradamus}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1941 films]]\n[[Category:1940s short films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by David Miller]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer short films]]\n[[Category:American biographical films]]\n[[Category:1940s biographical films]]\n{{short-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1941 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = More About Nostradamus\n| image          = More about Nostradamus -- screenshot.jpg\n| caption        = Titular screenshot\n| director       = [[David Miller (director)|David Miller]]\n| producer       = [[Carey Wilson (writer)|Carey Wilson]]\n| writer         = [[Carl Dudley]]\n| starring       = [[John Burton (actor)|John Burton]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography = Charles Lawton Jr.\n| editing        = Adrienne Fazan\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{film date|1941|1|18}}\n| runtime        = 11 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''More About Nostradamus''''' is a 1941 American [[short film]] directed by [[David Miller (director)|David Miller]]. In 1941 it was nominated for an [[Academy Award]] at the [[13th Academy Awards]] for [[Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film|Best Live Action Short Film, One-Reel]].<ref name=\"Oscars1941\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1941 |title=The 13th Academy Awards (1941) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=August 12, 2011|work=oscars.org| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110706093728/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/13th-winners.html| archivedate= July 6, 2011 <!--Added by DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |ur